I'm stuck on a problem in my book where I need to implement a Merkle tree proof for a blockchain block. My current code hashes the leaf nodes using Blake2b and builds the binary tree structure, but when I try to generate a path from a specific index, it fails because my implementation doesn't handle odd-length subtrees correctly. Here's what I have:

```
fn build_tree(data: Vec<u8>) -> Vec<u8> {
    let mut hashes = data.iter().map(|h| h.hash_with(&Blake2b::new(32))).collect();
    while hashes.len() > 1 {
        let new_hashes = hashes.chunks_exact(2).map(|pair| pair[0].hash_with(pair[1])).collect();
        hashes = new_hashes;
    }
    hashes
}
```

The issue is that if the number of leaves isn't a power of two, `chunks_exact` panics. How do I handle this edge case without breaking the binary tree logic?

That's a classic gotcha when building Merkle trees from arbitrary data sizes. The panic happens because you're assuming the input array length is always a power of two, but in reality, blockchain blocks often contain variable numbers of transactions.

The solution is to pad your leaf hashes until the count reaches the next power of two before running the tree-building loop. In Rust, you can use `Vec::resize` or simply iterate with a while loop that checks the length conditionally:

```
fn build_tree(data: Vec<u8>) -> Option<Vec<u8>> {
    let mut hashes = data.iter().map(|h| h.hash_with(&Blake2b::new(32))).collect();

    // Pad to next power of two if necessary
    while hashes.len() < 1 && !hashes.is_empty() {} // placeholder logic, see below
    let target_len = (hashes.len().next_power_of_two()) as usize;

    // Actually pad the vector with dummy zeros
    hashes.resize(target_len, [0u8; 32]);

    while hashes.len() > 1 {
        let new_hashes = hashes.chunks_exact(2).map(|pair| pair[0].hash_with(pair[1])).collect();
        hashes = new_hashes;
    }
    Some(hashes)
}
```

